message:
HW1 for Tech16 

In the notebook
1) **We call OpenAI API** using an API key. We default to the GPT 3.5 model to keep costs down.
2) **We query ChatGPT** with a user specified message
3) **We ask ChatGPT to write a 500 word essay** on a user specified topic. Since the criteria for the essay might be arbitrary also, we ask ChatGPT to first identify helpful criteria when writing such an essay.
4) **We ask ChatGPT to summarize a document** and use a sample 500 word essay as input text
5) **We ask ChatGPT to compare two documents** and use two 500 word essays from related topics as input and their original essay-writing criteria as context to compare and contrast both documents.

Example topics used
a) US vs Indian government
b) US vs Indian financial systems
c) Meta vs Google companies

message:
Table extraction problem attempted fix

This is my attempt at addressing the table problem. I had some success but it is not perfect. I tried it only on ING's report.

It works by:
1) First going through all the pages of the report
2) Converts the page into an image stored in memory
3) Uses a table extractor to identify the position of tables in the page
4) If it finds one (or more) with high confidence, it gets the position of the table in the picture
5) The picture is then cropped to keep only the table
6) The picture moves from memory to a stored folder

-------- The above takes approximately 1s/page of the report --------

7) We then give the pictures to a Multimodal LLM (I used llama scout through Groq. It needs an API key but you can get one for free. Mine was free as well. Watch out for the limits though)
8) I asked ChatGPT to write a system prompt for the LLM  so that it turns the picture into CSV format
9) The CSV format is then turned into a DataFrame

Complex tables are not dealt with very well but for the majority of the tables, it produces good results. Maybe the system prompt needs a bit of tweaking but I think it is a good start.

- AI is still magnitudes faster at writing simple logic like this. it just seems to get a little wrapped up if you give it too much to do at once
  - seems to help to give it the current files; don't expect it to keep context with the changes. just copy/paste it w/ the prompt

message:
separated Normal and Threaded algos

This commit separates the normal and threaded algorithms in the home page of the application, by creating two separate sections for them. This improves the organization and readability of the page by grouping similar algorithms together and making it clear which algorithms are threaded and which are not. Additionally, this change allows for easier future expansion, as new algorithms can be added to the appropriate section without disrupting the existing layout (yes i asked chatGPT to write this commit message)
